00:00:07.989 --> 00:00:09.220
I appreciate it.

00:00:09.220 --> 00:00:11.110
I know you're busy.

00:00:11.110 --> 00:00:15.290
I wrote "Bosstown"
a few years ago,

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:20.050
pretty much as the Big Dig
was finished, completed.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:23.380
I lived through the Big
Dig in the South End,

00:00:23.380 --> 00:00:27.050
before it was the South
End that you probably know.

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:29.430
And Boston's changed a lot.

00:00:29.430 --> 00:00:33.070
And the South End was
a very different place.

00:00:33.070 --> 00:00:35.410
Dorchester, Roxbury,
all these places

00:00:35.410 --> 00:00:42.310
that are now these are
unrecognizable coveted areas,

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:44.080
were once something
very different.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:47.110
And the Big Dig
really changed it.

00:00:47.110 --> 00:00:48.670
So there was
something that I just

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:52.270
felt I had to write because
I lived through those days

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:55.150
in the '80s, late
'80s, the '90s,

00:00:55.150 --> 00:01:02.080
working as a bike messenger and
as a mover, blue-collar work.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:04.269
That seems to have
kind of disappeared.

00:01:04.269 --> 00:01:10.090
Boston used to really
tolerate screw ups very well.

00:01:10.090 --> 00:01:14.350
And I was one of the prime
screw ups of the day.

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:18.310
But you could survive in
Boston, during those times,

00:01:18.310 --> 00:01:19.840
being a screw up.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:22.240
And I wanted to get
that down on paper,

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.410
just to prove that it existed.

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:27.110
And that's the way it was.

00:01:27.110 --> 00:01:31.360
So I'm just going to read
from the opening of the book.

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.550
The main character of the
book is a bike messenger,

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:35.740
a job that I did.

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:38.950
And the book actually has
a couple of voices in it;

00:01:38.950 --> 00:01:42.610
the voice of his father,
who suffers from Alzheimer's

00:01:42.610 --> 00:01:46.510
and used to deal poker
games, a roving poker game,

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:49.390
almost like a
Nathan-Detroit-style poker

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:53.380
game that was sanctioned both
by the mob and by city hall.

00:01:53.380 --> 00:01:57.080
His father has Alzheimer's
and knows things about Boston.

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:59.560
And as the streets
are being dug up,

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:02.680
secrets come up and
out of his head,

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:06.100
and also out of the streets,
along with the bodies.

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:08.889
So it's told from--

00:02:08.889 --> 00:02:11.410
my main character's
name is Zesty Meyers.

00:02:11.410 --> 00:02:14.310
There was a real Zesty
Meyers, actually,

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:17.200
which I'll hopefully
tell you about later.

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:18.850
The book is told in his voice.

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:21.940
But then it also
changes voices into what

00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:24.280
his father is thinking
or remembering

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:25.330
from the past in Boston.

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:28.435
So I'm actually going to read
just the opening portion out

00:02:28.435 --> 00:02:30.220
of the book, the prologue.

00:02:30.220 --> 00:02:34.580
And it starts out,
"Everybody in the game

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:36.620
thinks they're a shark.

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:40.040
This is how I see my
father, circa 1990.

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:43.790
He sits in a high-backed chair,
a deck of Bicycle playing cards

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:47.450
nestled in the palm of his left
hand, his right hand hovering

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:50.930
over the deck like a
magician summoning spirits.

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:52.820
He's wearing a
crisp white shirt,

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:54.440
unbuttoned at the collar.

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.800
The sleeves folded into
ruler-width rectangles that

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:01.140
sit just above the elbows,
framing his forearms

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:04.870
and the coiled muscles
that shift like snakes

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:07.250
under his tan, brown skin.

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:09.480
He is smiling, my
father, exposing

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:13.040
a yin yang of upper teeth,
separated horizontally

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:16.370
by a scraggly fault line,
where the bonding was attached

00:03:16.370 --> 00:03:19.970
but had yet to discolor to
match the upper portion.

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:22.340
His cheeks are
number 3 sandpaper,

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:25.820
flecked with dull nickel
silver, only partially covering

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:28.820
a lightning-bolt scar
under his bottom lip.

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:32.150
Smile lines run from
the corners of his mouth

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:35.630
into estuaries that reach
the edges of his eyes,

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:41.090
pools of battery acid lit with
a galaxy of pinprick lights

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:42.650
surrounding the pupils.

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:45.260
They are liar's eyes.

00:03:45.260 --> 00:03:48.110
Most of my earliest
memories are poker games,

00:03:48.110 --> 00:03:50.660
my father caressing
a deck of cards,

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:54.260
the sound of chips hitting
felt, darkened windows, or drawn

00:03:54.260 --> 00:03:56.480
shades in rooms,
dense with smoke

00:03:56.480 --> 00:03:59.090
and men who, during
breaks in the action,

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:01.400
would practice
staring into mirrors,

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:04.400
trying to erase the light
from their own eyes.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:06.590
On nights when my father
couldn't find someone

00:04:06.590 --> 00:04:09.080
to sit with me and
my brother, Zero,

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:12.320
he would haul us to
these games, where

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:15.560
we would pass the time reading
whatever books and papers were

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:16.760
lying about.

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:19.850
Or if the game was somewhere
with a kitchen or bar,

00:04:19.850 --> 00:04:22.490
Zero and I would fix the
mean sandwiches and drinks

00:04:22.490 --> 00:04:24.230
in exchange for tips.

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:28.940
Most often though, we just
sat behind, always behind,

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:32.140
our father and watch
the games unfold.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:35.120
Luck give way to
skill, friendly banter,

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:39.800
wind down into pressurized
silence or muttered curses.

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:41.840
It wasn't unusual
for Zero and me

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:44.150
to appear in school
directly from these marathon

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:48.650
games, our pockets bulging with
ones and fives, hair styled

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:51.460
with palm sweat, clothes
wrinkled and pungent

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:54.050
with cigar and cigarette smoke.

00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:56.870
It was not unusual
for me to wake

00:04:56.870 --> 00:05:00.770
from a deep sleep in the
nurse's office, Zero laid out

00:05:00.770 --> 00:05:04.400
beside me, his hand
squeezing imaginary cards,

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:08.270
dreams of royal flushes
and quad aces dancing

00:05:08.270 --> 00:05:10.660
behind sealed lids.

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:12.520
The Z brothers,
they would call us,

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:14.860
the narcoleptic
twins, though Zero

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:17.260
was nearly three years older.

00:05:17.260 --> 00:05:19.240
Whether this midday
catatonia brought

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:21.490
my father grief from the
school administration

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:24.700
is highly unlikely, since
those he played with were often

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:28.300
the school officials themselves,
or men otherwise hardwired

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.960
to the city's machinery;
politicians and their cronies,

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:35.410
ward bosses and their street
corner protegees, cops,

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:37.690
robbers, bag men,
businessmen, and thieves,

00:05:37.690 --> 00:05:39.520
who could tell the difference?

00:05:39.520 --> 00:05:41.590
These were the men
who made things happen

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:43.420
and problems disappear.

00:05:43.420 --> 00:05:45.940
Dangerous men who
brokered in favors,

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:48.880
cautiously-guarded secrets
that secured their positions

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.760
and livelihoods, a few
of which, remarkably

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.100
at odds with their
public personas, weighed

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:56.350
like liens on their conscience.

00:05:56.350 --> 00:05:59.230
Men who, I was to learn
later, had sometimes

00:05:59.230 --> 00:06:01.930
found the weight of those
secrets too great to keep

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:05.950
and would look into my father's
black eyes, those liar's eyes,

00:06:05.950 --> 00:06:08.680
and find whatever
it was they sought;

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:11.820
forgiveness, understanding.

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:15.580
In certain Central and
South American countries,

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:18.790
places where the governments
rotate in and out of power,

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:21.100
seemingly through
a revolving door

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:23.440
directly connected
to hell, there

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:27.100
existed a cadre of men and
women who hire themselves out

00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:29.770
as professional
hostages, stand-ins

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:33.400
for those taken from wealthy
families and held for ransom.

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:36.470
Though their loved ones ad been
removed from immediate danger,

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:41.050
the families rarely failed to
pay the ransom demands in order

00:06:41.050 --> 00:06:44.830
to preserve the honor of their
word, their family's good name.

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:47.500
Whether the hostages are
mistreated or tortured, live

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.390
or die, they could care less.

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:52.510
In their world,
reputation is everything.

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:55.450
My father operated under
much of the same principle,

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:58.210
only minus the cold, hard cash.

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:01.540
His word was bond because
generally, it was all we had.

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:04.630
My father was the place
secrets went to die,

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:06.760
never to see the light of day.

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:09.970
At least, that's what
everybody thought.

00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:12.570
But then, along
came the Big Dig,

00:07:12.570 --> 00:07:16.090
Boston's $20-billion
central artery project,

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:18.820
slicing through the city's
divided neighborhoods,

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:22.510
Charlestown, South Boston,
Chinatown, and East Boston,

00:07:22.510 --> 00:07:25.000
the South End, tearing
up the pavement,

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:29.610
exposing the bodies everyone
had figured were buried forever.

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:33.010
What my father knew, or
rather, what he remembered--

00:07:33.010 --> 00:07:36.220
as Alzheimer's crept in
and rendered his past

00:07:36.220 --> 00:07:38.770
a grab bag of
Etch-A-Sketch memories--

00:07:38.770 --> 00:07:42.580
seemed to shift as often
as Boston's topography.

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:45.790
The city and its history
were turned inside out,

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:48.650
one heaping shovel load
at a time, buildings

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:52.580
that had stood mute witness
to decades of fitful change

00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:55.420
were reduced to rubble
overnight and carted off

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:58.060
by convoys of trucks
that shook the ground

00:07:58.060 --> 00:08:00.370
like many earthquakes
as they barreled

00:08:00.370 --> 00:08:02.320
towards the harbor docks.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:06.040
Two-way streets were choked
into one-way passages, cement

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:08.500
barriers eliminating turns.

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:12.400
Exits and ramps were blocked
and turned around and rerouted

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:14.140
into makeshift outlets.

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:17.590
Rotaries were halved, draining
traffic back to the streets

00:08:17.590 --> 00:08:19.120
they had just escaped.

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:20.830
Sidewalks vanished.

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:22.510
Bridges led to nowhere.

00:08:22.510 --> 00:08:25.400
Streets disappeared completely.

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:29.020
And as the Earth rumbled,
shifted, and coughed up

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.559
its secrets, from every
crack, hole, and crevice,

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:35.770
the rats came out to play."

